column18: Pokedex Entry
There is a plant seed on its back right from the day this Pokémon is born. The seed slowly grows larger

There is a bud on this Pokémon's back. To support its weight, Ivysaur's legs and trunk grow thick and strong. If it starts spending more time lying in the sunlight, it's a sign that the bud will bloom into a large flower soon.

There is a large flower on Venusaur's back. The flower is said to take on vivid colors if it gets plenty of nutrition and sunlight. The flower's aroma soothes the emotions of people.

Prof. Lotus' Notes:

Gender Differences: You can tell a Venusaur is female based on whether flower has a seed in it.

There is a large flower on Venusaur's back. The flower is said to take on vivid colors if it gets plenty of nutrition and sunlight. The flower's aroma soothes the emotions of people.

Prof. Lotus' Notes:

Gender Differences: You can tell a Venusaur is female based on whether flower has a seed in it
The flame that burns at the tip of its tail is an indication of its emotions. The flame wavers when Charmander is enjoying itself. If the Pokémon becomes enraged, the flame burns fiercely.

Charmeleon mercilessly destroys its foes using its sharp claws. If it encounters a strong foe, it turns aggressive. In this excited state, the flame at the tip of its tail flares with a bluish white color.

Charizard flies around the sky in search of powerful opponents. It breathes fire of such great heat that it melts anything. However, it never turns its fiery breath on any opponent weaker than itself.

Charizard flies around the sky in search of powerful opponents. It breathes fire of such great heat that it melts anything. However, it never turns its fiery breath on any opponent weaker than itself.

Charizard flies around the sky in search of powerful opponents. It breathes fire of such great heat that it melts anything. However, it never turns its fiery breath on any opponent weaker than itself.
Squirtle's shell is not merely used for protection. The shell's rounded shape and the grooves on its surface help minimize resistance in water, enabling this Pokémon to swim at high speeds.

Its tail is large and covered with a rich, thick fur. The tail becomes increasingly deeper in color as Wartortle ages. The scratches on its shell are evidence of this Pokémon's toughness as a battler.

Blastoise has water spouts that protrude from its shell. The water spouts are very accurate. They can shoot bullets of water with enough accuracy to strike empty cans from a distance of over 160 feet.

Blastoise has water spouts that protrude from its shell. The water spouts are very accurate. They can shoot bullets of water with enough accuracy to strike empty cans from a distance of over 160 feet.
Caterpie has a voracious appetite. It can devour leaves bigger than its body right before your eyes. From its antenna, this Pokémon releases a terrifically strong odor.
The shell covering this Pokémon’s body is as hard as an iron slab. Metapod does not move very much. It stays still because it is preparing its soft innards for evolution inside the hard shell.

Butterfree has a superior ability to search for delicious honey from flowers. It can even search out, extract, and carry honey from flowers that are blooming over six miles from its nest.

Gender Differences: Female has black (purple in Gen 5) spots on her lower wings.
Weedle has an extremely acute sense of smell. It is capable of distinguishing its favorite kinds of leaves from those it dislikes just by sniffing with its big red proboscis (nose).

Kakuna remains virtually immobile as it clings to a tree. However, on the inside, it is extremely busy as it prepares for its coming evolution. This is evident from how hot the shell becomes to the touch.
Beedrill is extremely territorial. No one should ever approach its nest—this is for their own safety. If angered, they will attack in a furious swarm.
Beedrill is extremely territorial. No one should ever approach its nest—this is for their own safety. If angered, they will attack in a furious swarm.

Pidgey has an extremely sharp sense of direction. It is capable of unerringly returning home to its nest, however far it may be removed from its familiar surroundings.

Prof. Lotus' Notes: Despite it's name being a portmanteau of Pigeon and Budgie, Pidgey doesn't exhibit any outward traits of a Pigeon. It's more like a sparrow or chickadee (this link is further solidified by Pidgey having the shortest cry in the game). The link to pigeons exists behavior (sense of direction), as Pidgey are used as messenger birds much like pigeons (anime ep.164 Carrying On, National Pidgey Mail Service in Johto (Goldenrod), Sinnoh (Jubilife City), Kanto (Saffron City), Hoenn (Lilycove City), and Unova (Castelia City)).
Pidgey's natural predator is Ekans.

Pidgeotto claims a large area as its own territory. This Pokémon flies around, patrolling its living space. If its territory is violated, it shows no mercy in thoroughly punishing the foe with its sharp claws.

Prof. Lotus' Notes: Despite the name inferring that it's part of a Pigeon line, the design is more akin to that of an Osprey (a bird of prey). This Pokémon's etymology is deeply routed in the original game. Pidgeotto is a portmanteau of Pigeon and Diciotto (Italian for 18), Pidgey's level requirement to evolve in the mainline games.

This Pokémon has a dazzling plumage of beautifully glossy feathers. Many Trainers are captivated by the striking beauty of the feathers on its head, compelling them to choose Pidgeot as their Pokémon.

Prof. Lotus' Notes: Despite the name inferring that it's part of a Pigeon line, the design is more akin to that of an Eagle (a bird of prey). This Pokemon's name and pronunciation differ, unlike the pre-evolutions. Despite Ash calling this Pokémon Pid-gee-oht, the proper pronunciation of this Pokémon is actually Pid-jet, as the name is a portmanteau of Pigeon and Jet. This original pronunciation is heard in the PokéRap.
Pidgeot's design takes inspiration from the Golden Eagle, a link strengthened by it's Shiny form. The design also has Egyptian origin, as the eye markings and head design seem to be derived from the Gods Ra and Horus.

This Pokémon has a dazzling plumage of beautifully glossy feathers. Many Trainers are captivated by the striking beauty of the feathers on its head, compelling them to choose Pidgeot as their Pokémon.

Rattata is cautious in the extreme. Even while it is asleep, it constantly listens by moving its ears around. It is not picky about where it lives—it will make its nest anywhere.

Gender Differences: Female has shorter whiskers

Raticate’s sturdy fangs grow steadily. To keep them ground down, it gnaws on rocks and logs. It may even chew on the walls of houses.

Gender Differences: Female has shorter whiskers
Spearow has a very loud cry that can be heard over half a mile away. If its high, keening cry is heard echoing all around, it is a sign that they are warning each other of danger.
Fearow is recognized by its long neck and elongated beak. They are conveniently shaped for catching prey in soil or water. It deftly moves its long and skinny beak to pluck prey.

Ekans curls itself up in a spiral while it rests. Assuming this position allows it to quickly respond to a threat from any direction with a glare from its upraised head.

Prof. Lotus' Notes: The name Ekans is Snake backwards. They are Pidgey's natural preditor.
Ekan's design is a combination of rattlesnake (tail), facial marking of an indian cobra, with bands reminiscent to Diadophis punctatus or ringneck snake. The final design element could be inspired by the mythological creature Basilisk, as the Ekans line are poison type and can learn glare. Archbishop Isidore of Seville described the Basilisk as a creature with 'the king of snakes, due to its killing glare and its poisonous breath'.

This Pokémon is terrifically strong in order to constrict things with its body. It can even flatten steel oil drums. Once Arbok wraps its body around its foe, escaping its crunching embrace is impossible.

Prof. Lotus' Notes: Arbok mirrored backwords is Kobra. Arbok's design is modeled after the King Cobra. Arbok could be inspired by the mythological creature Basilisk, as it is a poison type and can learn glare. Archbishop Isidore of Seville described the Basilisk as a creature with 'the king of snakes, due to its killing glare and its poisonous breath'.
Because Arbok's unusually sounding name, it was put at the end of the Kanto Pokerap alongside Pidgeot.

Whenever Pikachu comes across something new, it blasts it with a jolt of electricity. If you come across a blackened berry, it’s evidence that this Pokémon mistook the intensity of its charge.

Prof. Lotus' Notes: Pikachu is a portmanteau of two Japanese onomatopoeia, first being 'Pika Pika' - Which means to Sparkle and 'Chu Chu' - the sound that mice make.

Gender Differences: Male Pikachu have squared off tails, whilst females have a heart shape

If the electrical sacs become excessively charged, Raichu plants its tail in the ground and discharges. Scorched patches of ground will be found near this Pokémon’s nest.

Gender Differences: Female Raichu do not have a pointed tail.
Burrows deep underground in arid locations far from water. It only emerges to hunt for food.
Sandslash’s body is covered by tough spikes, which are hardened sections of its hide. Once a year, the old spikes fall out, to be replaced with new spikes that grow out from beneath the old ones.

Nidoran has barbs that secrete a powerful poison. They are thought to have developed as protection for this small-bodied Pokémon. When enraged, it releases a horrible toxin from its horn.

Prof. Lotus' Notes: The name is a portmanteau of the Japanese borrowed word for Needle - ニドル (Nedoru), cnidocyte (thing in all poisonous animals) and rhino. Finally, 二度 or Nido in Japanese can be translated to 'two times' and this is often attributed to the Nidoran line splitting into male and female.

Gender Differences: Females in Nidoran family are light blue. Males are Purple.

When Nidorina are with their friends or family, they keep their barbs tucked away to prevent hurting each other. This Pokémon appears to become nervous if separated from the others.

Prof. Lotus' Notes: The name is a portmanteau of the Japanese borrowed word for Needle - ニドル (Nedoru), cnidocyte (thing in all poisonous animals) and rhino. The rina aspect is attributed to European languages like Italian or Spanish where a denotes female names.

Nidoqueen's body is encased in extremely hard scales. It is adept at sending foes flying with harsh tackles. This Pokémon is at its strongest when it is defending its young.

Prof. Lotus' Notes: The name is a portmanteau of the Japanese borrowed word for Needle - ニドル (Nedoru), cnidocyte (thing in all poisonous animals) and rhino.

The male Nidoran has developed muscles for moving its ears. Thanks to them, the ears can be freely moved in any direction. Even the slightest sound does not escape this Pokémon’s notice.

Prof. Lotus' Notes: The name is a portmanteau of the Japanese borrowed word for Needle, ニドル (Nedoru), cnidocyte (thing in all poisonous animals) and rhino. Finally, 二度 or Nido in Japanese can be translated to 'two times' and this is often attributed to Nidoran line splitting to male and female.

Gender Differences: Females in Nidoran family are light blue. Males are Purple.

Nidorino has a horn that is harder than a diamond. If it senses a hostile presence, all the barbs on its back bristle up at once, and it challenges the foe with all its might.

Prof. Lotus' Notes: The name is a portmanteau of the Japanese borrowed word for Needle - ニドル (Nedoru), cnidocyte (thing in all poisonous animals) and rhino. The rina aspect is attributed to European languages like Italian or Spanish where o denotes male names.

Nidoking's thick tail packs enormously destructive power. With one swing, it can topple a metal transmission tower. Once this Pokémon goes on a rampage, there is no stopping it.

Prof. Lotus' Notes: The name is a portmanteau of the Japanese borrowed word for Needle - ニドル (Nedoru), cnidocyte (thing in all poisonous animals) and rhino.

On every night of a full moon, groups of this Pokémon come out to play. When dawn arrives, the tired Clefairy return to their quiet mountain retreats and go to sleep nestled up against each other.

Prof. Lotus' Notes: Clefairy is unofically referred to as an Extraterrestrial Pokémon and are said to come to earth on meteorites as Cleffa.

Clefable moves by skipping lightly as if it were flying using its wings. Its bouncy step lets it even walk on water. It is known to take strolls on lakes on quiet, moonlit nights.

Prof. Lotus' Notes: Clefable is unofically referred to as an Extraterrestrial Pokémon. This link is strengthened by Clefairy needing a moon stone to evolve.

At the time of its birth, Vulpix has one white tail. The tail separates into six if this Pokémon receives plenty of love from its Trainer. The six tails become magnificently curled.

Prof. Lotus' Notes: Vulpix is a portmanteau of vulpine (something that resembles a fox), and six (number of tails it has). Vulpix is derived from Japanese folklore of a Kitsune 狐, which can be translated as fox or conversely, demon fox. The number of tails it has denotes how powerful the spirit is.

Legend has it that Ninetales came into being when nine wizards possessing sacred powers merged into one. This Pokémon is highly intelligent—it can understand human speech.

Prof. Lotus' Notes: Ninetales is a portmanteau of nine and tails (corruption of tails). Ninetales is derived from Japanese folklore of a Kitsune, more specifically 九尾の狐 - Kyubi no Kitsune, or 9 tails demon fox. 9 tails is the maximum a demon fox's tail can split into, and it is said that this is when it's magic is most powerful; think 9 tails demon fox from the Animé Naruto.
When this Pokémon sings, it never pauses to breathe. If it is in a battle against an opponent that does not easily fall asleep, Jigglypuff cannot breathe, endangering its life.
Wigglytuff’s body is very flexible. By inhaling deeply, this Pokémon can inflate itself seemingly without end. Once inflated, Wigglytuff bounces along lightly like a balloon.

Zubat avoids sunlight because exposure causes it to become unhealthy. During the daytime, it stays in caves or under the eaves of old houses, sleeping while hanging upside down.

Gender Differences: Female has smaller fangs

Golbat loves to drink the blood of living things. It is particularly active in the pitch black of night. This Pokémon flits around in the night skies, seeking fresh blood.

Gender Differences: Female has smaller fangs

During the daytime, Oddish buries itself in soil to absorb nutrients from the ground using its entire body. The more fertile the soil, the glossier its leaves become.

Prof. Lotus' Notes: Oddish has a fascinating branching evolution line, and my hunch is that is based on whether it fights off or doesn't fight off a parasitic infection that this Pokémon is susceptible to.

From its mouth Gloom drips honey that smells absolutely horrible. Apparently, it loves the horrid stench. It sniffs the noxious fumes and then drools even more of its honey.

Prof. Lotus' Notes: Gloom is based on the plant Rafflesia arnoldii a.k.a. the 'Stinking Corpse lily'. The plant got it's name because it smells like rotting flesh. Rafflesia is a parasite and it infects the plant host where a bud emerges. This has uncanny parallels to what happened to Oddish. The red discoloration of the leaves on it's head are also reminiscent to when plants are not getting nutrients, and this is because the parasite is leeching from the host Oddish. I suspect that the infected Oddish, Gloom, has two evolution lines because one is a scenario where the host cannot battle the infection, keeping it's susceptibility to spread the Parasite (Vileplume), and a line that was able to combat the Parasite and the healthy Oddish evolves to what it actually should have evolved into (Bellossom).
Female Gloom have one large spot per bud, whilst males are covered in spots.

Vileplume has the world’s largest petals. They are used to attract prey that are then doused with toxic spores. Once the prey are immobilized, this Pokémon catches and devours them.

Prof. Lotus' Notes: Vileplume is based on the plant Rafflesia arnoldii a.k.a. the 'Stinking Corpse lily'. The plant got it's name because it smells like rotting flesh. This is the final stage of the Parasite as it has now fully integrated itself with the host Oddish, the evolution line where the inverse is true is Bellossom.

Gender Differences: Female's petals have larger spots.

Paras has parasitic mushrooms growing on its back called tochukaso. They grow large by drawing nutrients from this Bug Pokémon host. They are highly valued as a medicine for extending life.

Prof. Lotus' Notes: Paras' name is derived from Parasite. The fungus on its back is inspired by the Ophiocordyceps unilateralis, more commonly known as the Cordyceps. This fungus takes over the host, slowly growing to the brain, where the host slowly starts to lose themselves and act according to the needs of the Parasite. The Cordyceps virus has medicinal potential in humans as it contains immunomodulatory, antiinfective, and anticancer agents.

Parasect is known to infest large trees en masse and drain nutrients from the lower trunk and roots. When an infested tree dies, they move onto another tree all at once.

Prof. Lotus' Notes: Parasect is a portmanteau of Parasite and Insect. The Cordyceps like fungus that it contracted as a Paras has fully taken over it's body, as can be seen by it's lifeless eyes. This host creature is no longer be seen as alive, and is merely a shell / puppet controlled by the virus. A similar concept can be seen in the video game the 'Last of Us'.
Venonat is said to have evolved with a coat of thin, stiff hair that covers its entire body for protection. It possesses large eyes that never fail to spot even minuscule prey.
Venomoth is nocturnal—it is a Pokémon that only becomes active at night. Its favorite prey are small insects that gather around streetlights, attracted by the light in the darkness.
Diglett are raised in most farms. The reason is simple— wherever this Pokémon burrows, the soil is left perfectly tilled for planting crops. This soil is made ideal for growing delicious vegetables.
Dugtrio are actually triplets that emerged from one body. As a result, each triplet thinks exactly like the other two triplets. They work cooperatively to burrow endlessly.

Meowth withdraws its sharp claws into its paws to slinkily sneak about without making any incriminating footsteps. For some reason, this Pokémon loves shiny coins that glitter with light.

Prof. Lotus' Notes: Meowth is based off a 招き猫 (Makineko) or 'beckoning cat'. They are believed to be a good luck charm. This connection is further strengthened by the 小判 (Koban) coin it has on its forhead. This Edo/Tokugawa period (1603–1868) coin is thought to bring good fortune.

Persian has six bold whiskers that give it a look of toughness. The whiskers sense air movements to determine what is in the Pokémon’s surrounding vicinity. It becomes docile if grabbed by the whiskers. The gem in its forehead glows on its own! It walks with all the grace and elegance of a proud queen.

Psyduck uses a mysterious power. When it does so, this Pokémon generates brain waves that are supposedly only seen in sleepers. This discovery spurred controversy among scholars. If it uses its mysterious power, Psyduck can’t remember having done so. It apparently can’t form a memory of such an event because it goes into an altered state that is much like deep sleep.

Prof. Lotus' Notes: Despite the Psy- prefix in the name coming from Psychic, Psyduck is not a has no Psychic partial typing. I think this is a nod to how confused this Pokemon is. You heard it here first.

The webbed flippers on its forelegs and hind legs and the streamlined body of Golduck give it frightening speed. This Pokémon is definitely much faster than even the most athletic swimmer. Golduck is the fastest swimmer among all Pokémon. It swims effortlessly, even in a rough, stormy sea. It sometimes rescues people from wrecked ships floundering in high seas.

Prof. Lotus' Notes: Despite the Gold- prefix in it's name, this Pokemon is blue. I think this is a nod to how confused this Pokemon is and it's poor memory allows it to remember that it was once Gold colour but in it's confusion, forgot it evolved. You heard it here first.

When Mankey starts shaking and its nasal breathing turns rough, it’s a sure sign that it is becoming angry. However, because it goes into a towering rage almost instantly, it is impossible for anyone to flee its wrath.
When Primeape becomes furious, its blood circulation is boosted. In turn, its muscles are made even stronger. However, it also becomes much less intelligent at the same time.

Growlithe has a superb sense of smell. Once it smells anything, this Pokémon won’t forget the scent, no matter what. It uses its advanced olfactory sense to determine the emotions of other living things.
Arcanine is known for its high speed. It is said to be capable of running over 6,200 miles in a single day and night. The fire that blazes wildly within this Pokémon’s body is its source of power.

Poliwag has a very thin skin. It is possible to see the Pokémon’s spiral innards right through the skin. Despite its thinness, however, the skin is also very flexible. Even sharp fangs bounce right off it.

Prof. Lotus' Notes: The spiral pattern on its belly is supposed to represent how the intestines of tadpoles are sometimes seen through their transparent skin.
The surface of Poliwhirl’s body is always wet and slick with a slimy fluid. Because of this slippery covering, it can easily slip and slide out of the clutches of any enemy in battle.
Poliwrath’s highly developed, brawny muscles never grow fatigued, however much it exercises. It is so tirelessly strong, this Pokémon can swim back and forth across the ocean without effort.

Abra needs to sleep for eighteen hours a day. If it doesn’t, this Pokémon loses its ability to use telekinetic powers. If it is attacked, Abra escapes using Teleport while it is still sleeping.

Prof. Lotus' Notes: The name is part of the magical incantation 'abracadabra'. Abra has qualities of a Goat and Fox which are deeply routed in sorcery and magic in Spanish and Japanese cultures. Abra's Japanese name is ケーシィ (Casey (I know, right?)), in reference to Edgar Cayce, a purported psychic famous for entering self-induced trances. Unlike the English counterpart, the Japanese names are all based on known mystics.

Kadabra holds a silver spoon in its hand. The spoon is used to amplify the alpha waves in its brain. Without the spoon, the Pokémon is said to be limited to half the usual amount of its telekinetic powers.

Prof. Lotus' Notes: As an extention to Abra, Kadabra's Japanese name is ユンゲラー (Yungerer) a corruption of Uri Geller, a psychic who claims to be able to be able to bend spoons with his Psychic Powers. Uri Geller sued Nintendo in the year 2000 for $60 Million, for the infringement of his likeness. The case is still believed to be ongoing (2018), and Kadabra has not been seen in Pokemon Trading Cards since 2003.

Gender Differences: Female Kadabra have smaller whiskers.

Alakazam’s brain continually grows, infinitely multiplying brain cells. This amazing brain gives this Pokémon an astoundingly high IQ of 5,000. This Pokémon holds its head up using its psychokinetic power instead. It has a thorough memory of everything that has occurred in the world. Alakazam uses its psychic powers to make the spoons it carries. Each spoon is an original that there’s only one of in the whole world.

Prof. Lotus' Notes: Alakazam's name in Japanese is フーディン (Fudin), at first glance this might seem weird, but this is because the japanese language does not have a Hu sound, Fu takes it place. If you were to translate it as Hudin, this is a corruption of Houdini, a great escapist. This is further supported by the chinese name 胡地 (Húdì).

Gender Differences: Female Kadabra have smaller whiskers.

Alakazam’s brain continually grows, infinitely multiplying brain cells. This amazing brain gives this Pokémon an astoundingly high IQ of 5,000. This Pokémon holds its head up using its psychokinetic power instead. It has a thorough memory of everything that has occurred in the world. Alakazam uses its psychic powers to make the spoons it carries. Each spoon is an original that there’s only one of in the whole world.

Prof. Lotus' Notes: Alakazam's name in Japanese is フーディン (Fudin), at first glance this might seem weird, but this is because the japanese language does not have a Hu sound, Fu takes it place. If you were to translate it as Hudin, this is a corruption of Houdini, a great escapist. This is further supported by the chinese name 胡地 (Húdì).

Gender Differences: Female Alakazam have smaller whiskers.

Machop’s muscles are special—they never get sore no matter how much they are used in exercise. This Pokémon has sufficient power to hurl a hundred adult humans.

Prof. Lotus' Notes: Up until the release of Pokemon Go, I did not know it had a tail. The game's ability to rotate the models changed my life.
Machoke undertakes bodybuilding every day even as it helps people with tough, physically demanding labor. On its days off, this Pokémon heads to the fields and mountains to exercise and train.

Machamp is known as the Pokémon that has mastered every kind of martial arts. If it grabs hold of the foe with its four arms, the battle is all but over. The hapless foe is thrown far over the horizon.

Prof. Lotus' Notes: Machamp and Alakazam in the original Games could only be received through trading. Both these stage 2 Pokemon have a gender distribution of 75% male. I believe that his inspiration comes from Vishnu or Ganesh from Hinduism, on account of the blue skin and multiple arms.

Bellsprout’s thin and flexible body lets it bend and sway to avoid any attack, however strong it may be. From its mouth, this Pokémon spits a corrosive fluid that melts even iron. A carnivorous Pokémon that traps and eats bugs. It appears to use its root feet to replenish moisture.
It spits out Poison Powder to immobilize the enemy and then finishes it with a spray of Acid. When hungry, it swallows anything that moves. Its hapless prey is melted inside by strong acids.
Lures prey with the sweet aroma of honey. Swallowed whole, the prey is melted in a day, bones and all.
Tentacool absorbs sunlight and refracts it using water inside its body to convert it into beam energy. This Pokémon shoots beams from the small round organ above its eyes.

Its 80 tentacles can stretch and contract freely. They wrap around prey and weaken it with poison. Tentacruel has large red orbs on its head. The orbs glow before lashing the vicinity with a harsh ultrasonic blast. This Pokémon’s outburst creates rough waves around it.

Prof. Lotus' Notes: The episode 'Tentacool and Tentacruel' was not aired in its original run of the Anime because of 9/11. The episode revolved around Tentacool and Tentacruel destroying a city and buildings in revolt.

The longer a Geodude lives, the more its edges are chipped and worn away, making it more rounded in appearance. However, this Pokémon’s heart will remain hard, craggy, and rough always.

Prof. Lotus' Notes: Geodude is a portmanteau of Geo (a prefix for things linked to the earth), Geode (a type of rock crystal, a link further expanded on with it's alolan form), and dude. Geodude was the very first Rock Pokémon in the Pokedex.

Rocks are Graveler’s favorite food. This Pokémon will climb a mountain from the base to the summit, crunchingly feasting on rocks all the while. Upon reaching the peak, it rolls back down to the bottom.

Prof. Lotus' Notes: Graveler's Japanese name is ゴローン (Goron), and avid Legend of Zelda fans would find that the rock species share the same name. This is because this is a play on words, ゴロゴローン (Goro Goron) is the onomatopoeia of rocks falling, a trait both of them share.
In the original Red and Blue version of the game, the sprite incorrectly had 4 limbs visible instead of 6. This was fixed in the Yellow version.

Golem live up on mountains. If there is a large earthquake, these Pokémon will come rolling down off the mountains en masse to the foothills below. To prevent them from rolling into the homes of people downhill, grooves have been dug into the sides of mountains to serve as guideways for diverting this Pokémon’s course. Once a year, this Pokémon molts, and its shed shell returns to the soil. This process creates enriched soil, so farmers collect the shells.

Prof. Lotus' Notes: Golem is designed like a turtle, with the cracks on its shell to be a reflection of the earth's techtonic plates.

Ponyta is very weak at birth. It can barely stand up. This Pokémon becomes stronger by stumbling and falling to keep up with its parent.

Prof. Lotus' Notes: Ponyta's evolution line based on mythical steeds: From greek mythology, Helois' steeds who helped full the sun. From Norse Mythology, Skinfaxi, the horse of that Dagr (day) into the sky with it's shining light. From Hindu mythology, Ashvins, two twin sons of the sun god, often referred to as 'Horsemen'.
Ponyta's Shiny form has a blue mane, suggesting that it has more efficient combustion, and therefore burns hotter. Despite this, Ponyta have the ability to control who gets burned by this flame.

Rapidash usually can be seen casually cantering in the fields and plains. However, when this Pokémon turns serious, its fiery manes flare and blaze as it gallops its way up to 150 mph.

Prof. Lotus' Notes: Rapidash are based off Unicorns as well as being an extention of the mythical creatures that inspired Ponyta. Rapidash' japanese name is simply ギャロップ (Gyaropu) which can be translated to Gallop.

A sweet sap leaks from its tail's tip. Although not nutritious, the tail is pleasant to chew on. Its long tail often breaks off. It doesn’t really feel any pain, though, and the tail grows back, so Slowpoke isn’t particularly bothered.

Prof. Lotus' Notes: Slowpoke is the only Pokemon that has the same weight as it's Pokedex entry number (when rounded). Slowpoke tails grow back, so they are constantly being targetted for cooking.

Slowbro’s tail has a Shellder firmly attached with a bite. As a result, the tail can’t be used for fishing anymore. This causes Slowbro to grudgingly swim and catch prey instead. It turns back into Slowpoke if its tail, along with Shellder, breaks off.

Prof. Lotus' Notes: The relationship that Slowpoke has with Shellder is parasitic. The Shellder on it's tail is constantly pumping poison into slowpoke to 'motivate' it to do what it likes.

Slowbro’s tail has a Shellder firmly attached with a bite. As a result, the tail can’t be used for fishing anymore. This causes Slowbro to grudgingly swim and catch prey instead. It turns back into Slowpoke if its tail, along with Shellder, breaks off.

Prof. Lotus' Notes: The relationship that Slowpoke has with Shellder is parasitic. The Shellder on it's tail is constantly pumping poison into slowpoke to 'motivate' it to do what it likes.

Magnemite floats in the air by emitting electromagnetic waves from the units at its sides. These waves block gravity. This Pokémon becomes incapable of flight if its internal electrical supply is depleted.

Prof. Lotus' Notes: IT BLOCKS GRAVITY... However, it can't learn levitate and is affected by ground moves.

Magneton emits a powerful magnetic force that is fatal to mechanical devices. As a result, large cities sound sirens to warn citizens of large-scale outbreaks of this Pokémon.

Prof. Lotus' Notes: It's weight is multiplied by ten (6kg to 60kg) when it evolves. This can be attributed to the stronger magnetic field it generates. However, this sounds like bad science. But then again, a single one blocks gravity, now there's 3 of them.

Farfetch’d is always seen with a stalk from a plant of some sort. In order to prevent their extinction, more people have made an effort to breed these Pokémon.

Prof. Lotus' Notes: This is the only Pokemon with an apostrophe in it's name. Farfetch'd are rare because they are always over-hunted for food.
The design of Farfetch'd may come from the Japanese idiom 鴨が葱を背負って来る (kamo ga negi wo shotte kuru), which translate to 'a duck comes bearing green onions', used in the sense of 'convenient turn of events', as you'd want to cook a duck that also brings the ingredients to cook it with. It's Japanese name is カモネギ (Kamonegi) further strengthening the connection to this idiom as 鴨 kamo (duck) and 葱 negi (spring/green onion) in their Kanji form is an abbreviation of the idiom.

Doduo’s two heads never sleep at the same time. Its two heads take turns sleeping, so one head can always keep watch for enemies while the other one sleeps.

Prof. Lotus' Notes: Somehow this apparent flightless Pokémon can learn 'Fly' and 'Steel Wing'. The Pokedex states it runs at speeds of 60km/h, this makes it 33.333....% faster than it's evolved form, Dodrio.

Gender Differences: Female Doduo have beige necks, whilst males have black necks.

Watch out if Dodrio’s three heads are looking in three separate directions. It’s a sure sign that it is on its guard. Don’t go near this Pokémon if it’s being wary—it may decide to peck you. Apparently, the heads aren’t the only parts of the body that Dodrio has three of. It has three sets of hearts and lungs as well, so it is capable of running long distances without rest.

Gender Differences: Female Dodrio have beige necks, whilst males have black necks.

Seel hunts for prey in the frigid sea underneath sheets of ice. When it needs to breathe, it punches a hole through the ice with the sharply protruding section of its head.

Prof. Lotus' Notes: Baby... I compare you to a SEEL from a rose...
Dewgong loves to snooze on bitterly cold ice. The sight of this Pokémon sleeping on a glacier was mistakenly thought to be a mermaid by a mariner long ago.

Grimer emerged from the sludge that settled on a polluted seabed. It constantly leaks a horribly germ-infested fluid from all over its body. As it moves, it loses bits of its body from which new Grimer emerge. This worsens the stench around it. Wherever Grimer has passed, so many germs are left behind that no plants will ever grow again. When two of these Pokémon's bodies are combined together, new poisons are created.

After recent environmental improvements, this Pokémon is now hardly seen at all. People speculate that it may go extinct at some point. As it moves, a very strong poison leaks from it, making the ground there barren for three years.
